re subsequently revealed to have been engaged in romantic liaisons at the time.The decades that followed the Pope’s visit were characterised by the increasing secularisation of Irish society. Boasting an impressive array of contributors from various backgrounds and expertise, the essays in the book attempt to trace the exact reasons for the progressive dismantling of the cultural legacy of Catholicism and the consequences this has had on Irish society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReligion and sociologyzIreland. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aCatholic identity.  aIrish Catholicism.  aIrish culture.  aSecularism.1 aCarroll Cochran, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarville, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleary, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCronin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaher, Eamon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaignant, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGarry, Patsy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Brien, Eugene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aO’Brien, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTighe-Mooney, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTwomey, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWall, Eamonn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle 